insta_description:
16 March 2020 
Saw this little guy near the Giant Forest Museum in Sequoia National park which a previous visitor had made of the last remnants of winter. Had to take a photo of him standing tall next to Sentinel which is the 43rd largest Giant Sequoia (Sequoiadendron giganteum) in the world and the 21st largest tree in Sequoia National Park. While the snowman is only about 4 inches tall and less than a day old, these ancient trees can be up to 3000 years old and are know to be the most massive trees on Earth. General Sherman, the largest tree as well as living thing in the world, is located in Sequoia and is a sight to see. Hope this little guy smiling and waving can bring a some brightness and solace to your day in light of the unfortunate events we are witnessing.

accessibility_caption: Photo by Kathryn Beals on March 16, 2020.
insta_description:
Today, our neighborhood was ordered to shelter in place. I can‚Äôt go to my studio. I‚Äôm anxious; as a mom, wife, sister, daughter, and small business owner. But, I‚Äôm here to tell you some of the positive things I‚Äôm seeing in my community.
.
I live in a townhouse complex, and though we are ‚Äúsocial distancing,‚Äù my neighbors have been sharing supplies and consolidating grocery trips to reduce exposure. The kids have been making drawings and notes for others in the complex, particularly older neighbors who are isolated. Someone left flowers on my porch today, and families are encouraging each other over texts.
.
When I couldn‚Äôt buy one of my art supplies because it wasn‚Äôt locally available anymore, I mentioned it in my stories. Multiple people - total strangers - offered to send me their extras for free because, as one person put it ‚ÄúI want you to keep making art‚Äù. I will keep making art - from my garage - and I‚Äôll keep posting it here. These stories are all why I chose the aspen leaf as my brand; it‚Äôs a symbol of community and I know we will get through this together.
.
What good stories and gestures are helping keep you focused today, as most of us are adjusting to this new normal?
.
Painting is Sanctuary, 20x24‚Äù acrylic on canvas, one of my older landscapes. The original belongs to my youngest son, now four. Prints are available on my website.

insta_description:
#SocialDistancing is the key!!!
.
For people who think they are young so #covid_19 won't affect them, remember this is not just about you. This is the time to be responsible. Your self quarantine is a step to help reduce the spread and help the healthcare system to cater to the cases that really need help. Flattening the spread/infection curve would actually help contain this pandemic and social distancing is the key to that! Also, people asking if travelling now is fine, since most of the places have turned into ghost towns; No It Is Not! The virus tends to stay in closed spaces and on surfaces for 3 hours to 15 days, do you really wanna risk getting the virus and being the cause of further spread?!?
.
It is not like a pandemic happens every year or you are asked to slow down and socially distance yourself every other year. This is rare and this step is important for everyone. Just enjoy your family time, pick up a hobby, get to that book that has been collecting dust and stay cautious.
.
On a non preachy note - #throwback to a #spring break in #SanFransisco #HalfMoonBay

insta_description:
Day 2: I'm always safe with her

Moms have such a magical way of making us feel alright. My mum flew in 10 days back to help me recover from my surgeries. As I struggled to keep my spirits and physical strength up in the past 3 months, my mum got me back on my feet in 10 days. I guess that's the magic of love. She flew out today and obviously I'm really blue but before she went, she made sure I started my daily drawings. So here I am mom! I'll miss you but I promise to be safe and cheerful even amidst our invisible enemy! 
My challenge this time will be themed around book covers and tidbits from my daily life! If you have a book in mind that you think I should read and then draw it's book cover, please feel free to DM! ü§ó

accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Enchanted Parties Montreal on March 16, 2020 tagging @lizabits. Image may contain: indoor
insta_description:
Today was the first day of our new routine. It amazes me how fast kids can adapt to new situations. After dinner Jonathan said he wanted the leftover stir fry for ‚Äúhomeschool lunch‚Äù tomorrow ü§ì‚úèÔ∏èüììüçé, and Mia showed me what she wrote in her gratitude journal tonight. What she was thankful for almost brought tears to my eyes as it was some of the most basic things. It is hard to find sth positive in these difficult times, but one thing I think we will all learn from this is to be more grateful for all the small and not so small things in our lives that we have always taken for granted. I am so thankful that my family and I are some of the lucky ones for whom all these restrictions haven‚Äôt had a huge impact on our daily routine yet. It is not lost upon me that some people aren‚Äôt as lucky and that their world has been turned upside down as they try to figure out how to work at the office, the supermarket ... or hospital while in need of someone at home to watch the kids, how to pay their rent or a mortgage without a steady income, or how to best protect a vulnerable family member from the dreaded virus.
I feel like I have done enough research in the last few days to educate myself on how to best protect my family and everyone else around me. There is nothing more I can do than we are already doing. I would now like to think of ways how I can help others make their lives easier in these difficult times. One person who is close to my heart is my friend Elizabeth @lizabits whom I have been collaborating with for quite some time now. She makes the most beautiful party decorations which you can find in her Etsy shop (link in my profile). As most parties and events have been cancelled, it is difficult for everyone who works in the event planning industry to stay afloat, especially if the situation worsens and/or lasts for an extended period of time and if it‚Äôs the only source of income. I will be sharing some of her amazing decorations in my stories these next few days in the hopes that some of you might consider buying a banner right now, even if you only need it at a later date. Elizabeth‚Äôs work is incredibly detailed and gorgeous and makes for great gifts too! ‚ù§Ô∏è

insta_description:
Heavy snow seen around Donner Pass/Truckee. ¬†So beautiful... This was during my spontaneous, snowy Reno outing with my cousin & Eugene... Our trip in summary: We left early Sunday morning (Feb 19). After taking in the beautiful snowy views along the way, we arrived at our Best Western Plus Boomtown Casino Hotel. For lunch, we ate at the lobster buffet there. After eating, we explored around Reno & stopped at the Wingfield Park. We then called it a day... After a sleepless evening (since I didn't have a bed), we headed home the very next morning, but things got interesting. Heavy snow was encountered on the way. We even got stranded around Truckee (by Donner Lake along Donner Pass Rd) since my cousin forgot her keys in the trunk when we were putting snow chains! After 2 chilling hours (while at the same time calling for help), we finally managed to open the back seat to get in the trunk. We then proceeded along I-80 slowly thru the whiteout conditions & finally got down the mountains safely, though plentiful rain continued to fall as we got back home. We made it back safely. Drive safe out there, fellas!
(Outing taken place February 19-20, 2017; Footage taken February 20, 2017)
*Weather scenario:
A powerful Pacific storm had moved thru NorCal overnight Sunday & was expected to impact the region thru Tuesday. The storm was to bring copious rainfall, heavy mountain snow & strong winds to the state. This winter has been quite active for atmospheric rivers in the West. Certainly, this season had knocked out the 5-year drought gripping the state. Also, much of the Sierras saw its rainiest/snowiest October-February period on record! "Heavy snow was to create dangerous conditions, with travel being severely impacted over the Sierra passes, including I-80," according to NWS. The snow amounts in the Sierras are mind‚Äìboggling; in many cases topping 500 inches which are some of the highest totals in memory...
location.name: Donner Pass

insta_description:
Many of us have been affected by the coronavirus; some to a greater scale than others. Whether the struggle is financial uncertainty or a medical issue, please take the appropriate precautions and know that many are praying over our government officials to make wise decisions. I may offend some by sharing my thoughts on this but I truly believe worrying and fearing this virus isn‚Äôt healthy or productive, but actually destructive to yours and other‚Äôs overall health.

Just to be clear, I believe in following government guidelines set by the CDC and taking appropriate actions toward avoiding further spread of this virus. 
My point is this a prime opportunity for all of us to think about the people we have around us who could really use some help. Think about someone who could be blessed with you buying them a meal or randomly Venmoing them a bit of money to help them get through this week due to their sudden loss of work. I encourage you to reach out to your neighbors, friends/family, and ask them what they‚Äôre struggling through and see if you can help out in some way, even if it‚Äôs by calling them throughout the week for updates.

Many people feel very alone and afraid and you have a beautiful opportunity to be a blessing in someone‚Äôs life. I don‚Äôt believe this is a time for isolation, rather it‚Äôs a time to think (without distractions) about who/what we really care about, and regardless of how long we‚Äôre quarantined or without jobs, we will prevail if we keep our hearts and minds focused on serving others and what we do have! You have the power to impact someone‚Äôs life for the better today. This is just the beginning of people realizing that we can stay positive and stand together during this recovery process. 
Prayer to a known God is more powerful than worrying about situations we can‚Äôt control.

insta_description:
A run with a view, puddles, roots, an elk and the ocean.

I‚Äôve set off a lot over the last few years to wander about for happiness and inspiration. I take in sights, sounds, and flavors, connect with people, and wear myself out on trails. It‚Äôs the most grounding thing for me aside from working with clay. Really I couldn‚Äôt function as an artist without it.

It takes constant work to shape your own world, and sometimes the unknowns of life feel daunting. I find reassurance knowing that one thing I can do is take ownership of my life.

I wrote a note to myself about that this fall saying: I realize the boundaries of our comfort zones are farther out than we think. We get lost in ideas of ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt‚Äù or ‚ÄúI lack,‚Äù when we can be anyone we want to be. Talk to the random person, say yes to an offer, walk into a strange place. You are your own limitations if you make them real.

Here‚Äôs to trying weird work situations, elbow bumps with strangers, getting faster, saying yes, saying no, cool river dips, open hearts, sleeping under starry skies, and everything in between. ‚ô•Ô∏è
